{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642331"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:37:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:37:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17932"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17932"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10646"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78780"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10646"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17932"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64129"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"7667"},{"type":"tags","id":"10061"},{"type":"tags","id":"11242"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24800"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78780"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following biosynthetic processes in cancer cells is supported by glycolysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nucleotide synthesis","Protein degradation","Fatty acid oxidation","Ketone synthesis","Cholesterol synthesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECancer cells frequently undergo increased glycolysis, even in aerobic conditions, a phenomenon known as the Warburg effect. This metabolic reprogramming supports the high energetic and biosynthetic demands of rapidly proliferating cancer cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENucleotide synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is supported by glycolysis, as intermediates from glycolysis, such as glucose-6-phosphate, are used in the pentose phosphate pathway to generate the precursor for nucleotide synthesis, ribose-5-phosphate..\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKetone synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs primarily in the liver during periods of low glucose availability and is not directly linked to glycolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtein degradation\u003C/strong\u003E is a catabolic process and does not rely on glycolysis for its function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholesterol synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily dependent on acetyl-CoA, which is derived from the breakdown of fatty acids and carbohydrates, but not directly from glycolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFatty acid oxidation\u003C/strong\u003E is a catabolic process that breaks down fatty acids to produce energy, and it is not directly supported by glycolysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cancer cells often rely on glycolysis for energy production and biosynthesis, even in the presence of oxygen, a phenomenon known as the Warburg effect.","Glycolysis in cancer cells provides intermediates for the synthesis of nucleotides and amino acids, which are essential for rapid cell proliferation."],"references":["Alfarouk KO, Verduzco D, Rauch C, Muddathir AK, Adil HH, Elhassan GO, Ibrahim ME, David Polo Orozco J, Cardone RA, Reshkin SJ, Harguindey S. Glycolysis, tumor metabolism, cancer growth and dissemination. A new pH-based etiopathogenic perspective and therapeutic approach to an old cancer question. Oncoscience. 2014 Dec 18;1(12):777-802. doi: 10.18632/oncoscience.109. Erratum in: Oncoscience. 2014 Dec 18;2(4):317. doi: 10.18632/oncoscience.158. PMID: 25621294; PMCID: PMC4303887.","Zhou D, Duan Z, Li Z, Ge F, Wei R, Kong L. The significance of glycolysis in tumor progression and its relationship with the tumor microenvironment. Front Pharmacol. 2022 Dec 14;13:1091779. doi: 10.3389/fphar.2022.1091779. PMID: 36588722; PMCID: PMC9795015.","Ganapathy-Kanniappan S. Molecular intricacies of aerobic glycolysis in cancer: current insights into the classic metabolic phenotype. Crit Rev Biochem Mol Biol. 2018 Dec;53(6):667-682. doi: 10.1080/10409238.2018.1556578. Epub 2019 Jan 22. PMID: 30668176.","Zheng J. Energy metabolism of cancer: Glycolysis versus oxidative phosphorylation (Review). Oncol Lett. 2012 Dec;4(6):1151-1157. doi: 10.3892/ol.2012.928. Epub 2012 Sep 20. PMID: 23226794; PMCID: PMC3506713."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64129"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17932"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64129"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T17:50:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T17:50:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10646"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78780"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel